  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">USAID anticipates making a $10M, five-year award to strengthen and scale up comprehensive HIV programming among uniformed personnel of the Uganda police, private security guards, and the Uganda tourism industry in the workplace. These target groups are Key Populations (KP) in Uganda. These populations are subject to deployments away from home and to places which are not adequately reached by essential services. This mechanism will build upon prior USG work aimed at improving HIV programming in the workplace environment. It will be a national program closely working with the Ministry of Internal Affairs, which oversees the Police and private security guards, as well as the Ministry of Tourism and Uganda Wild Life Authority. The overall objective of this mechanism is to improve health status among the target population, with a reduction in incidence of HIV/AIDS and other communicable diseases. This will be achieved through improved access to and utilization of quality HIV/AIDS prevention, care and treatment services. This project will contribute to the goals and objectives of the National HIV Prevention Strategy 2011-2015 and the Global Health Initiative (GHI) Strategy. This project will implement combination prevention approaches involving multiple prevention interventions of known efficacy in a geographic area at a scale, quality and intensity to impact the epidemic among the target population. Project monitoring and evaluation (M&amp;E) plans include quarterly reports to USAID with identified process indicators to monitor the project&#x2019;s progress towards achieving results and objectives, as well as PEPFAR semi-annual and annual reporting.</narrative>
  </description>
